Neuroblastoma Cell Line: Differential expression analysis with DESeq2

CCDL 2018

In this notebook, we’ll perform an analysis to identify the genes that are differentially expressed in MYCN amplified vs. nonamplified neuroblastoma cell lines.

These RNA-seq data are from Harenza, et al. Scientific Data. 2017..

More information about DESeq2 can be found in the excellent vignette from Love, Anders, and Huber from which this is adapted (see also: Love, Anders, and Huber. Genome Biology. 2014.)

DESeq2 takes unnormalized counts or estimated counts and does the following:

  • Estimates size factors
  • Estimates dispersion
  • Negative binomial generalized linear model fitting and Wald statistics

Dataset creation

# Create a DESeq2 dataset - remember Status is the variable of interest here
ddset <- DESeqDataSetFromTximport(txi = txi,
                                  colData = sample_meta_df,
                                  design = ~ Status)
some variables in design formula are characters, converting to factorsusing counts and average transcript lengths from tximport

Differential expression

Preparation

Let’s do some pre-filtering to keep rows with 10 or more reads total.

genes_to_keep <- rowSums(counts(ddset)) >= 10
ddset <- ddset[genes_to_keep, ]

We’ll want to use the “Nonamplified” samples as our reference. Let’s look at the levels of Status.

levels(ddset$Status)
[1] "Amplified"    "Nonamplified"

We can see that these are in alphabetical order, so “Amplified” samples would be the reference. We can use the relevel function to remedy this.

ddset$Status <- relevel(ddset$Status, ref = "Nonamplified")

# Check what the levels are now
levels(ddset$Status)
[1] "Nonamplified" "Amplified"

Visualize differentially expressed genes with a heatmap

Let’s get an overall picture of our results using a heatmap. Before we can do this, we will need to transform our data so that when we make the heatmap the genes are on a more similar scale and the heatmap is interpretable. We will use variance stabilizing transformation from DESeq2 to do this. Refer to the help page or the DESeq2 docs for more information.

# Use the vst function to transform the data
vst_data <- vst(ddset)
using 'avgTxLength' from assays(dds), correcting for library size

We need to extract the normalized gene matrix from the vst_data object.

vst_data <- assay(vst_data)

We will make a heatmap of only the significant genes, so let’s obtain the gene IDs that have an adjusted p-value less than 0.05.

# Filter to padj < 0.05 and then only extract the Genes
signif_genes <- deseq_df %>%
  dplyr::filter(padj < 0.05) %>%
  dplyr::pull(Gene)

Now we will use signif_genes to filter vst_data to only have significant genes’ data.

signif_vst_data <- vst_data %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  dplyr::filter(rownames(vst_data) %in% signif_genes)

Let’s make the results into a heatmap using the pheatmap package. We will use the scale = "row" argument so that the data is standardized by gene (i.e., will be made into z-scores). Standardizing the data by gene makes it so our heatmap is more easily interpretable despite how different genes’ distributions may be.

pheatmap::pheatmap(signif_vst_data, 
                   show_rownames = FALSE,
                   scale = "row",
                   colorRampPalette(c("deepskyblue",
                                      "black",
                                      "yellow"))(25))

If we want to save this heatmap as a PNG, we have to use the png function that is part of base R, run pheatmap::pheatmap again, and then use dev.off().

png(filename = heatmap_file)
# Use the same command to create the heatmap
pheatmap::pheatmap(signif_vst_data, 
                   show_rownames = FALSE,
                   scale = "row",
                   colorRampPalette(c("deepskyblue",
                                      "black",
                                      "yellow"))(25))
# This shuts down the current graphics device (the PNG we are saving)
dev.off()
null device 
          1

We can specify the dimensions and resolution of the PNG that is saved by supplying different arguments to the png function.

png(filename = heatmap_file, 
    width = 7, 
    height = 7, 
    units = "in", 
    res = 300)
# Heatmap time!
pheatmap::pheatmap(signif_vst_data, 
                   show_rownames = FALSE,
